I was thinking something like the following, which is user-driven via gcloud-aio in app rather than requiring polling from the external service:
```python
class SubscriberClient:
    # SNIP
    def get_subscription(...) -> Subscription:
        # SNIP
        return Subscriber.from_repr(result)

class Subscriber:
    def from_repr(cls, data: Dict[str, Any]) -> 'Subscriber':
        # SNIP
        return Subscriber(..., ack_deadline_seconds=['ackDeadlineSeconds']

    # https://cloud.google.com/pubsub/docs/reference/rest/v1/projects.subscriptions/patch
    def patch(self, ..., ack_deadline_seconds: Optional[int] = None) -> None:
        # SNIP
        if ack_deadline_seconds is not None:
            payload_body['ackDeadlineSeconds'] = ack_deadline_seconds
            self.ack_deadline_seconds = ack_deadline_seconds

async def consumer(subscription: Subscription, ...):
    while True:
        ack_deadline = subscription.ack_deadline_seconds
        # SNIP
```

The benefit there being that if users want to have their app code call `Subscription().patch(ack_deadline_seconds=42)`, it propagates to the running instance of the subscriber; but we don't need to worry about the extra logic of trying to keep our system in-sync with out-of-band changes.

